## Using off-PATH tools in agent commands

Invoke with the call operator and quoted absolute path:

```powershell
& 'c:\cmder\vendor\git-for-windows\cmd\git.exe' status
& 'c:\cygwin64\bin\jq.exe' '.' file.json
& 'C:\Program Files (x86)\GnuWin32\bin\make.exe' build-agent
```

Or prepend the directory to PATH for the session so the bare name works:

```powershell
$env:Path = "c:\cmder\vendor\git-for-windows\cmd;$env:Path"
git --version
```

## Verification (refresh inventory)

```powershell
& 'c:\cmder\vendor\git-for-windows\cmd\git.exe' --version
& 'c:\cygwin64\bin\jq.exe' --version
& 'C:\Program Files (x86)\GnuWin32\bin\make.exe' --version | Select-Object -First 1
```

## Agent conventions

- **git**: use full path or `$env:Path` prepend if `git` reports "not recognized"
- **grep in repo**: prefer Cursor `Grep` tool; in shell use `rg` (not `grep` on QC jump boxes)
- **make build-agent**: requires `make` + `git`; used by `capabilities-gateway`, `frontend`, `application-service` pipelines locally
- **kubectl**: comes from Docker Desktop; cluster context is user-managed (QC EKS via jump box)

## Line endings

- Always use unix style line endings for file contents that are used by our docker containers.  Havine Window/DOS line endings can cause issues in these containers.